To stand out to recruiters, you should frame this project as a Dual-State Full-Stack Cybersecurity Training Platform & Test Lab. Explain it not just as a "web app," but as a professional engineering tool designed to teach and validate defensive security.

Here is a guide on how to talk about this project in interviews, on your resume, and during networking.

1. The Elevator Pitch (30-Second Summary)
"I designed and built a production-grade web application that acts as a cybersecurity training lab. The platform is built using FastAPI, PostgreSQL, and Next.js 16 (Turbopack). What makes it unique is its dual-state architecture: it features isolated, intentionally vulnerable modules matching the OWASP Top 10 for security research, alongside fully patched, secure reference code for comparison. I also implemented a full STRIDE threat model, a 62-case manual QA test suite, and database-level PL/pgSQL triggers to log and redact audit trail logs automatically."

2. Key Technical Talking Points
🔹 Database Design & Auditing (3NF & PL/pgSQL)
What to say: "I designed the PostgreSQL database to strict Third Normal Form (3NF). To optimize authentication lookups, I separated core credentials from user profiles into a 1:1 relationship. I also built a database-level audit system using PL/pgSQL triggers that log DML mutations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) into an audit trail. For privacy and security compliance, the trigger automatically redacts password_hash values from the logs before they are written."
🔹 Backend Architecture (FastAPI Service Layer)
What to say: "On the backend, I used FastAPI and SQLAlchemy 2.0. I structured the application using the Service Layer and Repository Pattern to cleanly separate API routing from business logic. I wrote integration tests using Pytest running inside test-isolated transactions that roll back automatically to keep the test environment clean."
🔹 Frontend & Route Middleware (Next.js 16 & TypeScript)
What to say: "The frontend is a TypeScript Next.js 16 App Router application. I built custom navigation guards using Next.js Edge Middleware (proxy.ts). By reading cookie signatures on the server before rendering, the middleware restricts authenticated dashboard views and enforces role-based access control (RBAC), redirecting unauthorized users to a custom 403 page."
